        "id": "afbaa84ed0884e08bae04ff2c11927ae",
        "layout": "vertical",
        "purpose": "didigetthis",
        "type": "group"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "id": "vv15y665rs5mlxl",
                "text": "Comment"
              }
            ],
            "id": "95yvfrjgh84ylot",
            "type": "h1"
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "text": "When we used two-way tables in the categorical variables unit, it was to record values of two categorical variables for a concrete "
              },
              {
                "strong": true,
                "text": "sample"
              },
              {
                "text": " of individuals. In contrast, the information in a probability two-way table is for an entire "
              },
              {
                "strong": true,
                "text": "population"
              },
              {
                "text": ", and the values are rather abstract. If we had treated something like the delivery example as a sample, we would have recorded the actual numbers of on-time (and not-on-time) deliveries for samples of documents mailed with service A or B. In this section, the long-term probabilities are presented as being known. Presumably, those probabilities were based on relative frequencies recorded over many repetitions. "
              }
            ],
            "id": "d2306ac0e4f54bbc83590fadf59bd8af",
            "type": "p"
          }
        ],
